roughly talked to these people, if I haven=E2=80=99t investigated everythin=
g about them, if I haven=E2=80=99t learned their strengths and
their weaknesses,=E2=80=9D he added. =E2=80=9CAnd I think I owe that to the=
 president. And I think the better job I do, the better president he will b=
e.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Across the aisle, John Fetterman will be p=
erhaps the most closely watched senator during confirmations=E2=80=94anothe=
r member who can=E2=80=99t always be expected to vote his party=E2=80=99s l=
ine. Indeed, the soon-to-be senior senator from Pennsylvania confirmed on A=
BC that he will vote for
<strong>Elise Stefanik</strong> to serve as United Nations ambassador, alon=
g with <strong>Marco Rubio </strong>to run State.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">These, however, a=
re not controversial picks within the Democratic caucus. In Rubio=E2=80=99s=
 case, senators don=E2=80=99t like voting against other senators. And with =
Stefanik, there will almost certainly be other Democrats anxious to show th=
ey aren=E2=80=99t knee-jerk nays (even though they generally can=E2=80=99t =
stand her).
According to my conversations in Senate circles since her nomination, Stefa=
nik has cleared the bar of not disqualifying herself. Still, Fetterman=E2=
=80=99s enough of a maverick that he=E2=80=99s worth watching on other conf=
irmations. =E2=80=9CThere is going to be some that I will vote yes, and the=
re=E2=80=99s some maybe that I=E2=80=99ll vote no,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=
=9CBut nobody can accuse me of just saying I had a closed mind, or I just s=
aid no because Trump picked this person, or whatever.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
